{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is real filesystem watching semantics (recursive/subdirectory event delivery), which commonly differs by OS/watcher backend. A mock watcher can hide missed subdirectory events. Rejection gate: rejected Workflow/Agentic because behavior text has no AI/model step; rejected Integration because the behavior explicitly depends on real watch-event propagation from OS.","test_description":"Run the daemon as a real process against a temp watched directory. Create a nested subdirectory and write a file inside it. Assert exactly one transformed output appears in the output directory within timeout.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure boundary is local dedup algorithm/state over (path, time window). This can be caught with an in-memory clock/state test without OS or module handoff. Rejection gate: rejected Integration/System because behavior text targets dedup logic itself, not watcher/queue/OS interactions; rejected Agentic/Workflow because no model call.","test_description":"Instantiate dedup component with fake clock. Submit same path twice inside window and assert second is rejected; advance clock past window and assert request is accepted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.78,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly names OS multi-event emission; real failure appears in watcher+debounce/idempotency under actual OS event patterns. Mocked event streams can miss backend-specific duplication/timing quirks. Rejection gate: rejected Integration because wording requires real OS emission behavior; rejected Agentic/Workflow due no AI/model involvement.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real temp directory. Perform a write pattern known to trigger multiple events (create + append/rename). Verify only one processing output/side effect occurs for that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.91,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is an OS/inode lifecycle problem (watch handles invalidated on delete/recreate). In-process fakes often do not reproduce watcher detachment/rebind behavior. Rejection gate: rejected Integration because behavior requires real directory removal/recreation semantics while process stays alive; rejected Agentic/Workflow because no model decisions.","test_description":"Run daemon continuously, delete watched directory, recreate it at same path, then add a new file. Assert daemon processes the new file without process restart.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff/order logic: intake queue + metadata lookup + scheduler ordering. This can be validated by wiring those